   "type": "Feature",
   "properties": {
    "group": 12,
    "story": "Ivy Day in the Committee Room",
    "name": "Kavanagh's",
    "kind": "place",
    "gloss": "James Kavanagh's wine-rooms, 27 Parliament Street (between Essex Gate and Dame Street) — per Gifford 'a gathering place for Dublin politicians and for those in search of political favors'; the place where Father Keon and Mr Fanning are often found together.",
    "quote": "“Fanning and himself seem to me very thick. They’re often in Kavanagh’s together. Is he a priest at all?”",
    "srcText": "They’re often in Kavanagh’s together",
    "essay": "https://mappingdubliners.org/kavanaghs/",
    "source": "own"
   },
   "geometry": {
    "type": "Point",
    "coordinates": [
     -6.267631,
     53.34481
    ]
   }
  },
  {
   "type": "Feature",
   "properties": {
    "group": 8,
    "story": "A Little Cloud",
    "name": "Bewley's",
    "kind": "place",
    "gloss": "Bewley's tea and coffee merchants — the parcel of coffee Little Chandler forgets to bring home to Annie. Per Gifford most likely the Dame Street shop, a few steps east of City Hall on Chandler's route (placement approximate). As an Irish firm that broke the East India Company's tea monopoly in 1835, a quiet counterpoint to the story's theme of English economic dominance.",
    "quote": "It was a quarter to nine. Little Chandler had come home late for tea and, moreover, he had forgotten to bring Annie home the parcel of coffee from Bewley’s.",
    "srcText": "the parcel of coffee from Bewley’s",
    "essay": "https://mappingdubliners.org/bewleys/",
    "source": "own"
   },
   "geometry": {
    "type": "Point",
    "coordinates": [
     -6.2663,
     53.34425
    ]
   }
  },
  {
   "type": "Feature",
   "properties": {
    "group": 13,
    "story": "A Mother",
    "name": "Queen's Theatre",
    "kind": "place",
    "gloss": "The Queen's Royal Theatre, 209 Great Brunswick Street (now Pearse Street), near the Antient Concert Rooms — a popular venue for comic and musical acts, where the bass Mr Duggan once sang the king in Maritana; possibly the 1890 burlesque Miss Maritana rather than Wallace's opera (see the Mapping Dubliners essay). Demolished 1969.",
    "quote": "One night, when an operatic artiste had fallen ill, he had undertaken the part of the king in the opera of Maritana at the Queen’s Theatre.",
    "srcText": "Maritana at the Queen’s Theatre",
    "essay": "https://mappingdubliners.org/queens-theatre/",
    "source": "own"
   },
   "geometry": {
    "type": "Point",
    "coordinates": [
     -6.252907,
     53.344821
    ]
   }
  },
  {
   "type": "Feature",
   "properties": {
    "group": 4,
    "story": "Eveline",
    "name": "Italy",
    "kind": "place",
    "gloss": "The melancholy street-organ air Eveline hears on her last evening — Italian organ-grinders were a familiar sound of Dublin's streets; one of the story's array of far-off places set against Eveline's confinement.",
    "quote": "She remembered the last night of her mother’s illness; she was again in the close dark room at the other side of the hall and outside she heard a melancholy air of Italy. The organ-player had been ordered to go away and given sixpence. She remembered her father strutting back into the sickroom saying: “Damned Italians! coming over here!”",
    "srcText": "she heard a melancholy air of Italy",
    "essay": "https://mappingdubliners.org/italy/",
    "source": "own"
   },
   "geometry": {
    "type": "Point",
    "coordinates": [
     12.5,
     42.8
    ]
   }
  },
  {
